# Decide the Session-Start Briefing Contract

## Question

What does every agent wake up knowing? The rhizomatic briefing (claude
SessionStart hook) currently carries shallow session metadata. Decide: how
many observations and at what grain (today's index + N most-relevant atoms?
scoped to the session's repo/cwd?), ranking (recency vs relevance vs
graph-adjacency), staleness rule (durable decision pages outrank stale
observations — the temporal-gradient conflict rule, validated day one),
token budget per briefing, sensitive handling (include locally?), and WHICH
surfaces get it: claude hook, pi APPEND/extension, codex AGENTS — same
content everywhere or per-runtime shaping?

## Charter input (Joel, 2026-07-13): vision, inertia, and the annoyance bar

Joel: memory relates to VISION.md as "the vision an inertia of my systems" —
and the failure mode is a coding session "reminding me about some past
bullshit i don't care about." Principles for the grilling:

1. **Collision-triggered over ambient**: memory speaks when the session is
   about to CONTRADICT it, not when it merely remembers. Decisions already
   carry exit clauses (see files-are-truth: "named exit triggers", "do not
   relitigate") — recall surfaces a decision only when work approaches its
   territory, as guardrail not narration.
2. **Compile, don't converse**: vision belongs in machinery (validators,
   gates, charters) wherever possible; the briefing carries only what can't
   be compiled — current heading (active arc, frontier), ~3 lines, scoped
   to the session's repo/brief. Direction, not history.
3. **The annoyance bar is measurable**: a briefing line earns its place only
   if it changes what the session does. Consumption telemetry (fog) becomes
   interest decay — unengaged recall stops surfacing. Bar: not "worth
   recalling" but "worth interrupting with." Silence is the default state.
4. Vision docs sit at the TOP of the temporal gradient (canon); the
   reflector's monthly promotion feeds them; they outrank everything in
   recall conflicts.

## Answer (2026-07-13, grilled with Joel)

**Memories are skill-shaped, and memory loads in layers.**

Joel's model (verbatim shape): a memory has a very concise title + concise
description that UNFOLDS into a longer-form (still concise) document with
graph tendrils into previous memories — exactly the skill
progressive-disclosure pattern. The layers:

1. **Core memories (fused)**: principles, vision, standing law — loaded
   directly into the system prompt across the board, for everything. The
   mechanism ALREADY EXISTS: dark-wizard fleet grafts (CLAUDE.md blocks,
   .codex/AGENTS.md, .pi/APPEND_SYSTEM.md). What is missing is a curated
   CANON source: a small set of core-memory svx pages that compile into
   graft blocks (reflector monthly promotion feeds this layer; it stays
   deliberately tiny).
2. **Runtime memory index (ambient, skill-shaped)**: contextual/semantic
   memories relevant to the current work surface as title+description
   entries — scoped by repo/work-type, cheap in tokens — possibly literally
   via each runtime's skill mechanism (claude skills; pi skill-interpolation
   extension exists; codex equivalent TBD by prototype). The agent unfolds
   a memory only when work makes it relevant: collision-triggering by
   shape, not by watcher. This SUPERSEDES the heading-only briefing rec:
   the briefing = heading (arc/frontier/delta line) + the scoped memory
   index.
3. **Unfold (pull, cached)**: opening an index entry loads the page —
   served fast from cache (file read + qmd/Typesense as the lookup), the
   graph tendrils (wikilinks/backlinks) visible so the agent can walk to
   neighboring memories.
4. **Balance rule**: index entries are budgeted (small N, repo-scoped,
   interest-decayed via consumption telemetry); bodies never auto-load;
   core canon stays small enough to read in one breath. Continuity without
   pollution.

One content brain, three thin injectors: a single `joelclaw briefing`
computation feeding claude SessionStart, pi extension, codex AGENTS wiring.

Graduates: curate-core-memory-canon; build-memory-skill-index.
